    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis describes a severe intestinal infection caused by a bacterium called Clostridium difficile (C. difficile) that has come back after a previous infection. C. difficile bacteria release toxins that inflame the colon and cause severe diarrhea, abdominal cramping, and sometimes fever; it typically develops after someone has taken antibiotics that killed off their normal protective gut bacteria. Recurrent C. difficile is particularly concerning because it means the infection has returned at least once before, making it harder to treat and increasing the risk of serious complications.",
