    "plainEnglish": "Botulism food poisoning is a serious illness caused by eating food contaminated with a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum. This toxin paralyzes muscles throughout the body, starting with the face and throat and potentially affecting the muscles that control breathing. Symptoms include blurred vision, difficulty swallowing, facial weakness, and in severe cases, paralysis that may require mechanical ventilation to survive.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, internists, and infectious disease specialists commonly use this code in emergency departments and intensive care units when patients present with suspected botulism. The code appears in hospital admissions and may be seen on EOB statements for emergency care, though it is relatively uncommon as botulism is a rare condition in developed countries.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
