    "rawCode": "A053",
    "shortDesc": "Foodborne Vibrio parahaemolyticus intoxication",
    "longDesc": "Foodborne Vibrio parahaemolyticus intoxication",
    "plainEnglish": "Vibrio parahaemolyticus is a bacterium found in raw or undercooked seafood, especially oysters and shellfish, that causes food poisoning. When you eat contaminated seafood, the bacteria multiply in your digestive system and release toxins, leading to sudden diarrhea, abdominal cramps, nausea, vomiting, and sometimes fever—typically starting within 12-24 hours of eating the bad food. Most cases resolve on their own within 2-3 days, though severe dehydration can occur in vulnerable individuals.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, urgent care providers, and gastroenterologists commonly use this code when patients present with acute seafood-related food poisoning, typically in emergency department or urgent care settings. Infectious disease specialists may also use it for severe or complicated cases requiring hospitalization. This code appears on patient EOBs when emergency or urgent care visits involve treatment for bacterial food poisoning.",
