    "shortDesc": "Bacterial foodborne intoxication, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Bacterial foodborne intoxication, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes food poisoning caused by bacterial toxins, when the specific bacteria responsible hasn't been identified or confirmed. Instead of being infected by live bacteria, your body reacts to poisonous substances (toxins) that bacteria produced in contaminated food before you ate it. Symptoms typically include nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and abdominal cramps that usually appear within hours of eating the contaminated food and resolve within a few days.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency departments, urgent care centers, and primary care physicians use this code when treating patients with suspected foodborne illness that appears to be toxin-based rather than from a live infection. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements when someone seeks care for acute food poisoning and stool cultures or detailed testing haven't identified a specific bacterial culprit.",
