    "code": "A06.0",
    "rawCode": "A060",
    "shortDesc": "Acute amebic dysentery",
    "longDesc": "Acute amebic dysentery",
    "plainEnglish": "Acute amebic dysentery is a severe intestinal infection caused by a parasite called Entamoeba histolytica, which you typically catch by drinking contaminated water or eating contaminated food. The infection causes sudden, severe diarrhea (often bloody), severe abdominal cramping, and urgency to go to the bathroom repeatedly—symptoms that come on quickly and can be debilitating. This is different from regular diarrhea because the parasite actually damages the intestinal lining, which is why you may see blood in your stool.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, gastroenterologists, and emergency medicine physicians commonly diagnose and treat this condition, typically in an ER or acute care setting when patients present with severe bloody diarrhea and dehydration. This code appears on EOB statements when patients have been hospitalized or received urgent care for parasitic dysentery, and it may also be used by travel medicine clinics for patients returning from endemic areas.",
