    "shortDesc": "Chronic intestinal amebiasis",
    "longDesc": "Chronic intestinal amebiasis",
    "plainEnglish": "Chronic intestinal amebiasis is a persistent, long-term infection of the intestines caused by a parasite called Entamoeba histolytica, usually acquired by drinking contaminated water or eating contaminated food. Unlike the acute form that comes on suddenly, this chronic version develops slowly over weeks or months and causes ongoing symptoms like abdominal cramping, persistent diarrhea, weight loss, and general weakness. The parasite settles in the colon and continues to cause inflammation and tissue damage over an extended period.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, gastroenterologists, and primary care physicians commonly diagnose and treat this condition, typically identified through stool samples and imaging studies in outpatient or clinic settings. This code appears on EOB statements when patients receive office visits, lab work, or specialty care for parasitic infection management, and is especially relevant in cases involving recent travel to endemic regions or immigrant populations.",
