    "plainEnglish": "Amebic nondysenteric colitis is an infection of the colon caused by a parasite called Entamoeba histolytica, which is typically acquired by drinking contaminated water or eating contaminated food. Unlike the dysenteric form (which causes bloody diarrhea), this version causes inflammation and irritation of the colon without the presence of blood in the stool. Patients typically experience abdominal pain, cramping, and diarrhea, but the symptoms are generally less severe than the bloody form.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, gastroenterologists, and emergency medicine physicians use this code when diagnosing and treating parasitic infections of the colon. It commonly appears in cases presenting to urgent care or ER settings with persistent diarrhea and abdominal symptoms in patients with travel history to endemic areas, and may appear on EOB statements for patients requiring parasitic treatment and colonoscopy evaluation.",
