    "shortDesc": "Ameboma of intestine",
    "longDesc": "Ameboma of intestine",
    "plainEnglish": "An ameboma is a tumor-like mass or lump that forms in the intestines when a parasitic amoeba (a single-celled organism) invades and damages the intestinal wall over time. This condition develops in people who have had a chronic or severe amoebic infection, usually from drinking contaminated water in tropical or subtropical areas. Patients may experience abdominal pain, bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and a palpable mass in the belly that might be felt during examination.",
    "whoUses": "Gastroenterologists, infectious disease specialists, and general internists typically use this code when diagnosing patients with intestinal complications from amebic infection, usually in the context of outpatient evaluation, colonoscopy, or imaging studies. This code may appear on EOB statements for patients being treated for chronic parasitic infection or when surgical consultation is needed, though it is relatively uncommon in developed countries and more frequently encountered in travel medicine or tropical medicine practices.",
