    "longDesc": "Amebic liver abscess",
    "plainEnglish": "An amebic liver abscess is a pocket of pus and dead tissue in the liver caused by a parasite called Entamoeba histolytica, which is typically contracted by drinking contaminated water or eating contaminated food. The parasite travels through the bloodstream to the liver, where it destroys tissue and causes an infected collection to form. Patients typically experience abdominal pain, fever, and sometimes jaundice (yellowing of skin and eyes), and the condition is more common in people living in tropical or subtropical regions with poor sanitation.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, hepatologists (liver specialists), and emergency medicine physicians commonly diagnose and treat this condition, typically in hospital or outpatient settings after imaging studies (ultrasound or CT) confirm the abscess. This code appears on EOB statements for patients requiring drainage procedures, antiamoebic medications, or hospitalization related to this parasitic infection.",
