    "longDesc": "Amebic lung abscess",
    "plainEnglish": "An amebic lung abscess is a pus-filled cavity or pocket that forms in the lung tissue caused by a parasitic infection from amoebas (single-celled organisms). This usually happens when someone has had amebic dysentery (a severe intestinal infection) and the parasites spread through the bloodstream to the lungs, creating an infection that fills with infected fluid. Symptoms typically include chest pain, cough, shortness of breath, and sometimes coughing up bloody or foul-smelling mucus.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by pulmonologists, infectious disease specialists, and emergency medicine physicians, typically when diagnosing a patient presenting with respiratory symptoms and a history of or concurrent intestinal amebiasis. It appears in hospital settings, imaging follow-ups, and specialist consultations, and may show up on patient EOB statements as a secondary diagnosis code when treating respiratory complications from parasitic infection.",
