    "plainEnglish": "An amebic brain abscess is a serious infection of the brain caused by a single-celled parasite called Entamoeba histolytica, which typically enters the body through contaminated food or water. The parasite travels through the bloodstream and creates a pus-filled pocket (abscess) inside the brain tissue. This condition causes severe symptoms like high fever, severe headaches, confusion, seizures, and potentially life-threatening complications if not treated promptly with strong antiparasitic medications.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, neurologists, and emergency medicine physicians commonly diagnose and treat amebic brain abscess, typically in hospital or emergency department settings. This code appears on EOB statements when patients require hospitalization, imaging (MRI/CT scans), and intensive treatment with antiparasitic drugs. It is more common in patients from or traveling to areas with poor sanitation in tropical and subtropical regions.",
