    "shortDesc": "Cutaneous amebiasis",
    "longDesc": "Cutaneous amebiasis",
    "plainEnglish": "Cutaneous amebiasis is a skin infection caused by a parasitic amoeba (a microscopic single-celled organism) called Entamoeba histolytica. The infection typically enters the skin through cuts, wounds, or areas of broken skin and causes painful ulcers, sores, or lesions that may drain fluid and are often surrounded by inflamed, reddened tissue. This condition is rare in developed countries and is usually acquired in tropical or subtropical regions with poor sanitation, or through contact with contaminated water or soil.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, dermatologists, and emergency medicine physicians diagnose and treat cutaneous amebiasis, typically in clinic or urgent care settings after evaluation of suspicious skin lesions in patients with travel history. This code may appear on patient EOB statements if the infection requires specialized testing, antimicrobial therapy, or wound care visits.",
