    "longDesc": "Balantidiasis",
    "plainEnglish": "Balantidiasis is a parasitic infection caused by a microscopic organism called Balantidium coli that lives in the large intestine. You typically catch this infection by drinking contaminated water or eating contaminated food, often from contact with pigs or poor sanitation. People with this infection usually experience severe diarrhea, abdominal cramping, nausea, and sometimes bloody stools, though some people may have no symptoms at all.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, gastroenterologists, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing parasitic intestinal infections, typically in urgent care or office settings after stool testing. This code occasionally appears on patient EOB statements, particularly for patients from areas with poor sanitation or those with a history of pig exposure, though it is relatively rare in developed countries.",
