    "longDesc": "Giardiasis [lambliasis]",
    "plainEnglish": "Giardiasis is an intestinal infection caused by a parasite called Giardia that you typically get from drinking contaminated water or eating contaminated food. The parasite attaches to your small intestine and causes diarrhea, cramping, bloating, and nausea that can last weeks if untreated. Most people get this infection from traveling to areas with poor sanitation or drinking from contaminated lakes and streams.",
    "whoUses": "Gastroenterologists, family medicine doctors, infectious disease specialists, and emergency room physicians use this code when diagnosing patients with persistent diarrhea and intestinal symptoms. It commonly appears in clinic visits for stool testing and parasite confirmation, and may show up on EOB statements for patients seeking treatment of travel-related or foodborne illness.",
