    "shortDesc": "Cryptosporidiosis",
    "longDesc": "Cryptosporidiosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Cryptosporidiosis is a digestive system infection caused by a tiny parasite called Cryptosporidium that you can pick up from contaminated water, food, or infected animals. The infection settles in your intestines and causes watery diarrhea, stomach cramps, nausea, and sometimes fever—symptoms that can last from a few days to several weeks. People with weakened immune systems (like those with HIV/AIDS) can get especially severe, long-lasting cases.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, gastroenterologists, and primary care doctors commonly diagnose and treat cryptosporidiosis, typically based on stool samples or lab tests. This code appears in outpatient clinic visits, urgent care settings, and hospitalizations when the infection is severe, and it may show up on patient EOBs when insurance covers diagnostic testing and treatment related to parasitic infections.",
