    "shortDesc": "Isosporiasis",
    "longDesc": "Isosporiasis",
    "plainEnglish": "Isosporiasis is a parasitic infection of the small intestine caused by tiny organisms called Isospora, which you typically get by eating contaminated food or water. The infection causes chronic diarrhea, abdominal cramping, nausea, and weight loss, and it's more common and severe in people with weakened immune systems, especially those with HIV/AIDS. The parasites live in your intestines and damage the lining, preventing your body from absorbing nutrients properly.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, gastroenterologists, and tropical medicine doctors diagnose and treat isosporiasis, typically in office visits or outpatient settings after stool samples confirm the parasite. This code is more commonly seen in patients from endemic areas (Central/South America, Africa, Asia) or immunocompromised individuals, and may appear on EOB statements for those requiring antiparasitic medications and follow-up testing.",
