    "plainEnglish": "Adenoviral enteritis is an infection of the small intestine caused by a virus called adenovirus. This virus irritates the intestinal lining, causing inflammation and symptoms like diarrhea, abdominal cramping, nausea, and sometimes vomiting or low-grade fever. It's usually self-limiting, meaning it goes away on its own within a few days to a week, and is spread through contact with contaminated food, water, or infected individuals.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, pediatricians, and gastroenterologists commonly use this code when diagnosing viral diarrhea, typically in office visits or urgent care settings. Emergency department physicians may also use it when patients present with acute gastroenteritis symptoms. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements for outpatient visits and may appear if lab work or imaging was performed to rule out other causes.",
