    "shortDesc": "Calicivirus enteritis",
    "longDesc": "Calicivirus enteritis",
    "plainEnglish": "Calicivirus enteritis is an infection of the intestines (small bowel and colon) caused by a virus called calicivirus, which spreads through contaminated food or water or contact with infected people. This infection causes inflammation and irritation of the gut lining, leading to symptoms like acute diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, stomach cramps, and sometimes low-grade fever. Most people recover on their own within a few days with fluids and rest, though the condition can be especially uncomfortable and sometimes dangerous in young children, elderly people, or those with weak immune systems.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, pediatricians, gastroenterologists, and emergency department providers typically diagnose and manage calicivirus enteritis during office visits or ER evaluations. This code commonly appears on patient EOB statements when someone seeks care for acute gastrointestinal symptoms, as providers need to document the viral cause for proper treatment guidance and infection control measures.",
