    "rawCode": "A150",
    "shortDesc": "Tuberculosis of lung",
    "longDesc": "Tuberculosis of lung",
    "plainEnglish": "Tuberculosis of the lung is a serious bacterial infection caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis that primarily affects the lungs. People with this condition typically experience persistent cough (often lasting more than 3 weeks), chest pain, coughing up blood or bloody sputum, fever, night sweats, and unintentional weight loss. The infection spreads through airborne droplets when an infected person coughs or sneezes, and can range from latent (dormant) to active disease that requires extended antibiotic treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonologists, infectious disease specialists, primary care physicians, and emergency medicine doctors commonly use this code when diagnosing and treating patients with active tuberculosis, typically in clinical offices, hospitals, and TB specialty clinics. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements, insurance claims, and hospital bills since TB treatment involves long-term medication management and monitoring.",
