    "longDesc": "Tuberculosis of intrathoracic lymph nodes",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means a person has a tuberculosis (TB) infection that has spread to the lymph nodes inside the chest cavity, between the lungs and heart. Lymph nodes are small bean-shaped immune organs that help fight infection, and when TB bacteria settle in them, they become swollen and inflamed. Patients may experience chest pain, persistent cough, or notice swollen lymph nodes visible on a chest X-ray, though many people have no obvious symptoms at first.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonologists, infectious disease specialists, and primary care physicians commonly use this code when diagnosing TB, typically during evaluation of a persistent cough or abnormal chest imaging in office or hospital settings. This code frequently appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing TB testing, imaging (chest X-rays or CT scans), and antibiotic therapy for documented intrathoracic TB infection.",
