    "rawCode": "A1781",
    "shortDesc": "Tuberculoma of brain and spinal cord",
    "longDesc": "Tuberculoma of brain and spinal cord",
    "plainEnglish": "A tuberculoma of the brain and spinal cord is a serious infection caused by the tuberculosis (TB) bacterium that has spread to form a tumor-like mass in the central nervous system. This condition develops when TB bacteria travel through the bloodstream and settle in brain or spinal cord tissue, creating a localized collection of infected and inflamed material. Patients may experience severe headaches, neurological deficits like weakness or numbness, seizures, fever, or cognitive changes, depending on where the tuberculoma is located and how large it has grown.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by infectious disease specialists, neurologists, and neurosurgeons, typically in hospital inpatient settings, emergency departments, or during imaging/diagnostic workup. It may also appear in consultation notes when TB is being treated across multiple organ systems. This serious infection code commonly appears on hospital EOB statements and insurance claims for imaging (MRI/CT), lumbar punctures, and anti-tuberculosis drug therapy.",
