    "shortDesc": "Tuberculous meningoencephalitis",
    "longDesc": "Tuberculous meningoencephalitis",
    "plainEnglish": "Tuberculous meningoencephalitis is a serious infection caused by tuberculosis (TB) bacteria that spreads to the brain and the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord. This causes inflammation of both the meninges (protective membranes) and the brain tissue itself, leading to symptoms like severe headache, high fever, confusion, stiff neck, sensitivity to light, and potentially seizures. If left untreated, this type of TB infection can cause permanent brain damage or death.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, neurologists, and emergency medicine physicians diagnose and treat this condition, typically in hospital inpatient settings or intensive care units. This code appears on EOBs for patients receiving IV antibiotics, imaging studies (CT or MRI of the brain), lumbar punctures, and prolonged hospitalization for TB treatment.",
