    "rawCode": "A1809",
    "shortDesc": "Other musculoskeletal tuberculosis",
    "longDesc": "Other musculoskeletal tuberculosis",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means a patient has tuberculosis (TB) that has spread to bones, joints, or muscles rather than staying in the lungs. TB is a serious bacterial infection usually caught by breathing in infected droplets from another person, and when it spreads to the musculoskeletal system, it can cause chronic pain, swelling, weakness, and gradual destruction of the affected bones or joints. The infection develops slowly over weeks or months and may not cause obvious symptoms at first, but eventually leads to visible deformity, difficulty moving, or drainage from affected areas.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, orthopedic surgeons, and pulmonologists commonly use this code during evaluation and ongoing treatment of extrapulmonary TB, typically in hospital inpatient settings or specialty clinics. This code appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing imaging (X-rays, MRI), biopsies, or long-term anti-tuberculosis drug therapy, and may also be used in public health reporting since TB is a reportable disease.",
