    "plainEnglish": "Retroperitoneal tuberculosis is a bacterial infection caused by tuberculosis (TB) that specifically affects the retroperitoneum—the space behind the abdominal organs and lining where the kidneys, major blood vessels, and other structures sit. This happens when TB bacteria spread from the lungs or other infected areas through the bloodstream into this deep abdominal space, causing inflammation, scarring, and potentially forming infection-filled pockets. Patients typically experience chronic abdominal pain, fever, weight loss, and sometimes notice a hard mass in the back of the abdomen, though symptoms can be subtle and develop slowly over weeks or months.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, internal medicine physicians, and sometimes gastroenterologists or surgeons diagnose and treat retroperitoneal tuberculosis, usually in hospital or outpatient settings during diagnostic workup (imaging and biopsy) and long-term antibiotic therapy. This code may appear on patient EOB statements when TB-specific imaging (CT scan), hospital consultations, or specialized infectious disease care is billed, and it's particularly common in regions with higher TB prevalence or in immunocompromised patients.",
