    "shortDesc": "Tuberculous iridocyclitis",
    "longDesc": "Tuberculous iridocyclitis",
    "plainEnglish": "Tuberculous iridocyclitis is an eye infection caused by tuberculosis bacteria that inflames the iris (the colored part of your eye) and the ciliary body (muscles that help focus the eye). This occurs when TB spreads from the lungs or other parts of the body to the eye, causing pain, redness, blurred vision, and sensitivity to light. It's a serious condition that can lead to permanent vision damage if not treated with anti-tuberculosis medications.",
    "whoUses": "Ophthalmologists and infectious disease specialists diagnose and treat this condition, typically in an outpatient clinic setting after TB has been identified elsewhere in the body. This code may appear on EOB statements for patients with active tuberculosis who develop eye complications, though it is relatively uncommon in developed countries.",
