    "longDesc": "Tuberculosis of other sites",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes tuberculosis (TB) infection that has spread to parts of the body other than the lungs, bones, or other commonly affected sites that have their own specific codes. Tuberculosis is a serious bacterial infection spread through the air, and while it typically affects the lungs, it can damage almost any organ—such as the kidneys, intestines, lymph nodes, or skin—causing inflammation, tissue damage, and progressive illness if left untreated. Symptoms depend on which organ is affected but may include fever, weight loss, fatigue, and dysfunction of the affected area.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, pulmonologists, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing and treating extrapulmonary TB in various clinical settings including office visits, hospital admissions, and during follow-up care for TB patients. This code commonly appears on patient EOB statements and medical records when TB testing confirms infection in non-pulmonary sites, often requiring extended antibiotic therapy and monitoring.",
