    "code": "A20.0",
    "rawCode": "A200",
    "shortDesc": "Bubonic plague",
    "longDesc": "Bubonic plague",
    "plainEnglish": "Bubonic plague is a serious bacterial infection caused by the bacterium Yersinia pestis, typically spread to humans through bites from infected fleas that live on rodents like rats. The infection causes large, painful, swollen lymph nodes (called buboes) that appear in the groin, armpit, or neck, along with fever, chills, and general illness. While this disease is rare today due to modern sanitation and antibiotics, it was historically one of the most deadly pandemics; it can be fatal without prompt antibiotic treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and public health authorities use this code when diagnosing and treating plague cases, typically in emergency department or inpatient hospital settings. This code rarely appears on routine patient EOB statements since plague cases are extremely uncommon in developed countries and are often reportable to public health agencies; when they do occur, hospital and specialty billing will include this diagnosis.",
