    "shortDesc": "Cellulocutaneous plague",
    "longDesc": "Cellulocutaneous plague",
    "plainEnglish": "Cellulocutaneous plague is a form of the bubonic plague infection that affects both the skin and underlying tissues, causing painful, swollen lumps (called buboes) typically in the groin, armpit, or neck area, along with skin ulcers or blackened tissue at the infection site. This happens when the plague bacterium (Yersinia pestis) enters through a bite or cut in the skin and spreads to nearby lymph nodes and tissues. Patients typically develop fever, chills, and rapidly worsening skin infections that can become life-threatening if not treated with antibiotics.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and general practitioners use this code when diagnosing and treating plague infections, typically in emergency department or hospital inpatient settings. This is a rare code in modern practice in developed countries but may appear in public health surveillance and epidemiological reporting; it is unlikely to be a common finding on typical patient EOB statements outside of endemic regions.",
