    "code": "A20.2",
    "rawCode": "A202",
    "shortDesc": "Pneumonic plague",
    "longDesc": "Pneumonic plague",
    "plainEnglish": "Pneumonic plague is a severe lung infection caused by the bacterium Yersinia pestis, the same organism responsible for the historical 'Black Death.' The infection develops when plague bacteria spread to the lungs, causing symptoms like cough, chest pain, difficulty breathing, and the coughing up of blood-tinged sputum. This is the most dangerous form of plague because it spreads directly from person to person through respiratory droplets and can progress to fatal sepsis or death within days if not treated immediately with antibiotics.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, pulmonologists, and emergency medicine physicians use this code, typically in hospital settings given the severity and need for immediate isolation and treatment. While rare in modern developed countries, it would be diagnosed in emergency departments or during inpatient admissions and may appear on EOB statements as a serious reportable infection requiring specialized care and infection control measures.",
