    "code": "A20.3",
    "rawCode": "A203",
    "shortDesc": "Plague meningitis",
    "longDesc": "Plague meningitis",
    "plainEnglish": "Plague meningitis is a severe infection of the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord caused by the bacteria that causes plague (Yersinia pestis). This occurs when the plague infection spreads from the lungs or lymph nodes into the central nervous system, leading to inflammation of the protective layers covering the brain. Patients experience a combination of plague symptoms (fever, fatigue, body aches) along with meningitis symptoms such as severe headache, stiff neck, sensitivity to light, confusion, and potentially seizures or coma.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists use this code when diagnosing and treating plague that has progressed to meningitis, typically in ER and intensive care settings. This is a rare but life-threatening condition that may be reported to public health authorities; it would appear on EOB statements for patients receiving emergency and critical care treatment for this condition.",
