    "code": "A20.7",
    "rawCode": "A207",
    "shortDesc": "Septicemic plague",
    "longDesc": "Septicemic plague",
    "plainEnglish": "Septicemic plague is a severe, life-threatening form of the plague (caused by the bacterium Yersinia pestis) where the infection spreads throughout the bloodstream instead of being contained to one area. This occurs when plague bacteria multiply rapidly in the blood and can affect multiple organs, causing symptoms like fever, chills, weakness, bleeding under the skin (black patches), and organ failure. Without immediate antibiotic treatment, this form of plague is often fatal.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and critical care doctors use this code when diagnosing and treating patients with bloodstream plague infections, typically in emergency department or intensive care unit settings. This code rarely appears on routine patient EOB statements due to the rarity of plague cases in developed countries, but when it does occur, it represents a medical emergency requiring hospitalization and specialized treatment.",
