    "plainEnglish": "Plague is a serious bacterial infection caused by the bacterium Yersinia pestis, which is typically spread through infected fleas or rodents. While most people think of plague as the 'Black Death' from history, it still occurs today and can cause severe fever, swollen lymph nodes, and tissue damage if left untreated. This code represents uncommon or atypical forms of plague that don't fit the more common presentations (like bubonic or pneumonic plague).",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and public health officials use this code, typically in hospital or emergency department settings when diagnosing a confirmed case of plague. This code is rare in routine outpatient practice and would be notable on an EOB statement, as plague requires mandatory reporting to public health authorities and typically involves hospitalization.",
