    "plainEnglish": "Cutaneous anthrax is a skin infection caused by the bacterium Bacillus anthracis, which enters the body through cuts or breaks in the skin. It typically starts as a small, itchy bump that develops into a painless, black sore (called an eschar) surrounded by swelling within 2–6 days. This is the most common and least dangerous form of anthrax infection, and it responds well to antibiotics if treated promptly.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by infectious disease specialists, dermatologists, primary care physicians, and emergency medicine providers when evaluating patients with suspected anthrax skin infections, typically in an office visit, urgent care, or emergency department setting. It may appear on EOB statements for patients exposed to anthrax through contaminated animal products, animal contact, or in rare cases of bioterrorism exposure.",
