    "shortDesc": "Pulmonary anthrax",
    "longDesc": "Pulmonary anthrax",
    "plainEnglish": "Pulmonary anthrax is a serious lung infection caused by inhaling spores from the bacterium Bacillus anthracis, which is found in soil and can contaminate animal products or be released as a biological agent. The infection causes the anthrax bacteria to grow in the lungs and can lead to severe respiratory symptoms including cough, chest pain, shortness of breath, and fever, potentially progressing to shock and organ failure if left untreated. This is a life-threatening condition that requires immediate medical intervention with antibiotics.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonary anthrax is typically diagnosed and treated by infectious disease specialists, pulmonologists, and emergency medicine physicians in hospital settings, often involving the CDC and public health authorities due to its serious nature and potential as a bioterrorism agent. This code appears in emergency department and inpatient admission records; it is extremely rare in typical office settings and would likely appear on EOB statements only in cases of actual infection requiring hospitalization.",
