    "plainEnglish": "Gastrointestinal anthrax is a serious infection caused by eating meat or food contaminated with anthrax bacteria (Bacillus anthracis). This form of anthrax affects the stomach and intestines, causing severe abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea (sometimes bloody), and loss of appetite. It's the rarest form of anthrax but can be life-threatening if not treated quickly with antibiotics.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and internal medicine doctors use this code when diagnosing and treating anthrax exposure through contaminated food. It appears in emergency department visits, hospital admissions, and public health investigations, and may show on patient EOB statements when anthrax is confirmed as the diagnosis requiring specialized treatment.",
