    "shortDesc": "Anthrax sepsis",
    "longDesc": "Anthrax sepsis",
    "plainEnglish": "Anthrax sepsis is a life-threatening blood infection caused by the bacterium Bacillus anthracis, which typically enters the body through contaminated skin wounds, inhalation of spores, or rarely through contaminated food. When anthrax bacteria spread into the bloodstream and multiply uncontrollably, it triggers a severe systemic inflammatory response that can damage multiple organs and cause shock, organ failure, and death if not treated immediately with antibiotics. Patients with anthrax sepsis experience high fever, extreme weakness, low blood pressure, and potentially rapid deterioration.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, infectious disease specialists, and intensive care doctors use this code when treating anthrax infections that have progressed to sepsis in hospital or emergency department settings. This is a rare but potentially reportable diagnosis most commonly seen in bioterrorism scenarios or occupational exposures in individuals working with infected animals or contaminated materials; it would appear on EOB statements for hospitalized patients receiving emergency sepsis management.",
