    "plainEnglish": "Spirillosis is a rare bacterial infection caused by Spirillum minus, which is typically transmitted to humans through the bite of an infected rat. The infection causes symptoms such as fever, chills, swollen lymph nodes, and a characteristic rash that may appear weeks or even months after the initial rat bite. If left untreated, the condition can recur and cause serious complications, though it is generally curable with appropriate antibiotic treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists and emergency medicine physicians typically diagnose and code spirillosis, often in patients presenting with fever and a history of rat exposure or bite. This code appears in both acute care settings (ER visits) and infectious disease office consultations, and it may show up on patient EOB statements when the condition requires specialist evaluation or hospitalization for treatment.",
