    "plainEnglish": "Streptobacillosis is a rare bacterial infection caused by the bacterium Streptobacillus moniliformis, typically transmitted through the bite or scratch of an infected rat or contaminated food and water. The infection causes fever, rash, joint pain, and swollen lymph nodes, and if left untreated, can lead to serious complications affecting the heart and other organs. It's sometimes called rat-bite fever, though it can occur without an obvious bite wound.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and primary care doctors typically diagnose and treat streptobacillosis, usually in an urgent care or ER setting when a patient presents with unexplained fever and history of rat exposure. This code occasionally appears on EOB statements for patients with confirmed or suspected rat-bite fever requiring laboratory testing and antibiotic treatment.",
