    "shortDesc": "Cutaneous erysipeloid",
    "longDesc": "Cutaneous erysipeloid",
    "plainEnglish": "Cutaneous erysipeloid is a skin infection caused by a bacterium called Erysipelothrix rhusiopathiae, typically acquired from handling infected animals, contaminated meat, or fish. The infection causes a painful, red, swollen, and sometimes itchy rash, usually on the hands or fingers, that may spread slowly if left untreated. Unlike the more serious systemic form of the disease, this localized skin version remains limited to the outer layers of skin and is generally treatable with antibiotics.",
    "whoUses": "This code is commonly used by dermatologists, primary care physicians, occupational health doctors, and infectious disease specialists when evaluating workers in the meat processing, fishing, or veterinary industries who develop characteristic skin lesions. It may appear in office visits or occupational health clinic encounters and can show up on EOB statements when specialty dermatology evaluation or infectious disease consultation is billed.",
