    "longDesc": "Erysipelothrix sepsis",
    "plainEnglish": "Erysipelothrix sepsis is a serious bloodstream infection caused by the bacterium Erysipelothrix rhusiopathiae, which typically enters the body through cuts or wounds on the skin, especially in people who handle raw meat, fish, or animal products. When this bacteria spreads into the blood, it can cause fever, chills, and potentially life-threatening complications if not treated with antibiotics. This condition is relatively rare but most common in occupational settings like butchering, fishing, or veterinary work.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists when treating patients with confirmed systemic Erysipelothrix infection. It typically appears in hospital/inpatient settings where blood cultures confirm the diagnosis, and may be seen on EOB statements for patients requiring IV antibiotic therapy and intensive care management.",
