    "shortDesc": "Leptospirosis icterohemorrhagica",
    "longDesc": "Leptospirosis icterohemorrhagica",
    "plainEnglish": "Leptospirosis icterohemorrhagica is a severe form of leptospirosis, a bacterial infection you can get from contact with infected animal urine (usually from rats or other rodents) in water or soil. This dangerous type causes jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes from liver damage), kidney failure, bleeding into the lungs, and can lead to shock or death if untreated. Patients typically develop high fever, severe muscle pain, vomiting, and bleeding problems within a week or two of exposure.",
