    "longDesc": "Aseptic meningitis in leptospirosis",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a type of meningitis (infection of the fluid and membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord) caused by leptospirosis, a bacterial infection spread through contact with infected animal urine, commonly from rats or other wildlife. The meningitis is \"aseptic,\" meaning it develops without pus-forming bacteria directly infecting the brain lining, and typically causes symptoms like severe headache, stiff neck, fever, and sometimes light sensitivity. It's a serious but potentially treatable condition if caught early and managed with appropriate antibiotics.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists commonly diagnose and treat this condition in hospital settings, emergency departments, or during infectious disease consultations. This code is typically used when a patient with confirmed or suspected leptospirosis develops meningitis symptoms, and it may appear on EOB statements for hospitalized patients or those with serious infections requiring specialized care.",
