    "code": "A28.1",
    "rawCode": "A281",
    "shortDesc": "Cat-scratch disease",
    "longDesc": "Cat-scratch disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Cat-scratch disease is an infection you can get from a cat scratch or bite, usually from a kitten or young cat that carries a bacterium called Bartonella henselae. The infection causes swollen, painful lymph nodes (often near the scratch), and you might develop a fever, fatigue, or a small bump at the scratch site that looks like a pimple. Most people recover on their own within a few weeks, though the swollen lymph nodes can last for months.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, infectious disease specialists, and urgent care or ER providers typically diagnose and code cat-scratch disease during office visits or emergency evaluations. Pediatricians frequently encounter this condition since children are more likely to be scratched by cats. This code commonly appears on patient EOB statements as it's a common reportable infection requiring documentation for medical records and insurance purposes.",
