    "code": "A28.2",
    "rawCode": "A282",
    "shortDesc": "Extraintestinal yersiniosis",
    "longDesc": "Extraintestinal yersiniosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Extraintestinal yersiniosis is a bacterial infection caused by Yersinia bacteria that spreads beyond the intestines to other parts of the body, such as lymph nodes, joints, or the bloodstream. This infection typically starts after eating contaminated food or water and causes symptoms like fever, swollen lymph nodes, joint pain, or abdominal pain. Unlike typical food poisoning that stays in the gut, this infection invades deeper tissues and requires antibiotic treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and primary care doctors diagnose and treat this condition, typically in office visits, urgent care, or hospital settings when systemic infection is suspected. This code may appear on patient EOB statements when laboratory confirmation of Yersinia is documented and the infection has spread beyond the intestinal tract.",
