    "longDesc": "Other specified zoonotic bacterial diseases, not elsewhere classified",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes uncommon bacterial infections that humans catch from animals but don't fit neatly into other disease categories. These are rare zoonotic diseases (spread from animals to people) caused by bacteria, such as infections from handling infected wildlife, farm animals, or pets. Symptoms vary widely depending on which specific bacterium caused the infection, but they might include fever, skin lesions, swollen lymph nodes, or localized inflammation at the bite or wound site.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and primary care doctors use this code when diagnosing unusual animal-related bacterial infections that don't match standard diagnoses like brucellosis or leptospirosis. It typically appears in hospital or urgent care settings where the patient presents with signs of infection after animal exposure, and may show up on EOBs when specialized lab tests or imaging are needed to identify the specific bacterial pathogen.",
