    "shortDesc": "Zoonotic bacterial disease, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Zoonotic bacterial disease, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "This code is used when a patient has a bacterial infection that came from an animal, but doctors haven't identified exactly which animal or which specific bacteria caused it. Zoonotic diseases are illnesses that naturally spread from animals to humans—like through bites, scratches, handling infected animals, or consuming contaminated meat or dairy. Symptoms vary widely depending on the type of infection but might include fever, rash, swollen lymph nodes, or localized wound infections.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine doctors, and primary care physicians use this code when a patient presents with signs of an animal-borne bacterial infection but the specific organism hasn't been identified yet—often in urgent care or ER settings. This code typically appears on EOB statements as a temporary or interim diagnosis while cultures and tests are pending, and is often replaced with a more specific code once the bacteria is identified.",
