    "code": "A30.2",
    "rawCode": "A302",
    "shortDesc": "Borderline tuberculoid leprosy",
    "longDesc": "Borderline tuberculoid leprosy",
    "plainEnglish": "Borderline tuberculoid leprosy is a form of Hansen's disease (leprosy) caused by a bacterial infection that affects the skin and nerves. In this milder type, patients develop only a few patches of skin discoloration or numbness, typically on one side of the body, because their immune system is relatively strong and able to partially control the infection. The affected areas lose sensation and may become discolored, but unlike severe leprosy, there is less widespread nerve damage and disfigurement.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, dermatologists, and tropical medicine physicians primarily use this code, typically during clinic evaluations or when treating patients in endemic regions where leprosy remains active. This code appears in the diagnosis section of medical records and EOB statements for patients receiving antibacterial treatment for Hansen's disease, though it is rare in developed countries.",
