    "code": "A30.3",
    "rawCode": "A303",
    "shortDesc": "Borderline leprosy",
    "longDesc": "Borderline leprosy",
    "plainEnglish": "Borderline leprosy is an intermediate form of Hansen's disease, a chronic bacterial infection caused by Mycobacterium leprae that primarily affects the skin and nerves. In this type, patients show signs between the milder and more severe forms of leprosy—they may develop patches of skin discoloration with reduced sensation, nerve thickening, and mild to moderate nerve damage, but the condition is less severe than lepromatous leprosy. People with borderline leprosy can transmit the disease to others and require prompt antibiotic treatment to prevent progression and nerve damage.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists and dermatologists typically diagnose and manage borderline leprosy, primarily in endemic regions or in patients with travel history to affected areas. This code appears in specialty clinic visits, infectious disease consultations, and dermatology evaluations; it is less common on standard EOBs since leprosy is rare in developed countries but may appear in centers specializing in tropical or infectious diseases.",
