    "code": "A30.5",
    "rawCode": "A305",
    "shortDesc": "Lepromatous leprosy",
    "longDesc": "Lepromatous leprosy",
    "plainEnglish": "Lepromatous leprosy is the most severe form of Hansen's disease, a chronic bacterial infection caused by Mycobacterium leprae that primarily affects the skin and nerves. In this type, the bacteria multiply extensively throughout the body, causing widespread skin lesions that appear as nodules, plaques, and thickened patches, often with a characteristic 'lion-like' appearance of the face due to swelling. Patients typically have high numbers of bacteria in their lesions and are highly contagious; they also experience progressive nerve damage, numbness, weakness, and can develop serious complications affecting the eyes, nose, and organs if left untreated.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, dermatologists, and tropical medicine physicians diagnose and manage lepromatous leprosy, typically in outpatient clinic settings or specialized leprosy treatment centers. This code appears in medical records, referral documentation, and occasionally on EOB statements, though it is now rare in developed countries and primarily encountered in endemic regions or among patients with international travel history.",
