    "rawCode": "A309",
    "shortDesc": "Leprosy, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Leprosy, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Leprosy is a chronic infectious disease caused by bacteria that primarily affects the skin and nerves, leading to numbness, weakness, and disfiguring sores or lesions. When the type or severity of leprosy cannot be determined or is not further specified, it's coded as 'unspecified.' The infection spreads through prolonged respiratory contact with an untreated person and can cause permanent nerve damage if left untreated, though it responds well to antibiotics when diagnosed early.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, dermatologists, and primary care physicians use this code, typically in referral settings, specialized clinics, or when diagnosing a patient with leprosy symptoms but without confirmed classification into the specific lepromatous, tuberculoid, or borderline subtypes. While leprosy is rare in developed countries, this code may appear on EOB statements for international patients or those from endemic regions seeking treatment in the United States.",
