    "rawCode": "A311",
    "shortDesc": "Cutaneous mycobacterial infection",
    "longDesc": "Cutaneous mycobacterial infection",
    "plainEnglish": "Cutaneous mycobacterial infection is a skin disease caused by bacteria called mycobacteria (relatives of the tuberculosis germ) that invade the outer layers of your skin. You might see slow-growing bumps, nodules, ulcers, or discolored patches on your skin, usually on areas exposed to water or injury. These infections typically progress slowly over weeks or months and are usually painless, though they can occasionally drain or become infected with other bacteria.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists, infectious disease specialists, and primary care physicians commonly use this code when diagnosing and treating skin infections caused by nontuberculous mycobacteria, typically during office visits or dermatology clinic evaluations. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements for outpatient dermatology treatment and may be used in conjunction with procedures like skin biopsies or cultures.",
