    "longDesc": "Disseminated mycobacterium avium-intracellulare complex (DMAC)",
    "plainEnglish": "Disseminated mycobacterium avium-intracellulare complex (DMAC) is a serious bacterial infection caused by germs that spread throughout the body, affecting multiple organs like the lungs, lymph nodes, and intestines. This infection typically occurs in people with very weakened immune systems, particularly those with advanced HIV/AIDS. Symptoms can include fever, night sweats, weight loss, fatigue, and abdominal pain, though signs may develop slowly over weeks or months.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, HIV/AIDS clinicians, and pulmonologists commonly diagnose and manage DMAC, typically in hospital settings or specialized outpatient clinics caring for immunocompromised patients. This code frequently appears on EOB statements for patients with advanced HIV disease requiring antimicrobial therapy and intensive monitoring.",
