    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a bacterial infection caused by mycobacteria—a type of slow-growing germ that's harder to treat than common bacteria. Mycobacteria include the species that cause tuberculosis and leprosy, but this code is used when doctors know a mycobacterial infection is present but haven't identified exactly which type it is yet. Symptoms vary widely depending on which organs are affected, but may include fever, weight loss, fatigue, and persistent cough or skin problems.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, pulmonologists, and primary care physicians use this code during initial diagnosis when mycobacterial infection is suspected but testing hasn't confirmed the specific organism. It's typically used in hospital settings, urgent care, or specialist offices when culture results are pending or inconclusive. This code commonly appears on EOB statements as a temporary or interim diagnosis before more specific mycobacterial codes are assigned.",
