    "shortDesc": "Listerial sepsis",
    "longDesc": "Listerial sepsis",
    "plainEnglish": "Listerial sepsis is a life-threatening blood infection caused by bacteria called Listeria monocytogenes. This bacterium typically enters the body through contaminated food (often unpasteurized dairy products, deli meats, or raw vegetables) and spreads into the bloodstream, triggering a severe whole-body inflammatory response. Symptoms include fever, chills, muscle aches, nausea, and potentially confusion or altered consciousness, and the condition requires immediate antibiotic treatment in a hospital setting.",
