    "longDesc": "Oculoglandular listeriosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Oculoglandular listeriosis is a rare infection caused by the bacterium Listeria monocytogenes that affects the eye and the lymph nodes near the eye. The infection typically develops after the bacteria enter through a break in the skin or mucous membrane, often from contaminated food (like unpasteurized dairy or deli meats) or contact with infected animals. Symptoms include redness and irritation of the eye, a sore or ulcer on the eyelid or conjunctiva, and swollen, tender lymph nodes in front of the ear or under the jaw.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists and ophthalmologists commonly diagnose and treat this condition, often in hospital or specialty clinic settings. The code may appear on EOB statements for patients who require IV antibiotics or specialized eye evaluations, though this is a relatively uncommon diagnosis that typically follows blood culture results or direct bacterial identification.",
