    "shortDesc": "Listerial endocarditis",
    "longDesc": "Listerial endocarditis",
    "plainEnglish": "Listerial endocarditis is an infection of the heart's inner lining (endocardium) caused by a bacterium called Listeria monocytogenes. This bacterium typically enters the bloodstream through contaminated food (like deli meats, unpasteurized dairy, or soft cheeses) and seeds the heart valves, causing inflammation, fever, and potentially life-threatening valve damage. Patients usually experience persistent fever, fatigue, shortness of breath, and heart murmurs that a doctor can detect with a stethoscope.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, cardiologists, and emergency medicine physicians diagnose and treat this condition, typically in hospitalized patients requiring blood cultures, echocardiography, and prolonged IV antibiotics. This code appears in hospital discharge summaries and may be referenced on EOB statements for inpatient cardiology or infectious disease consultations, though it is relatively uncommon in outpatient settings.",
