    "plainEnglish": "Listeriosis is a serious bacterial infection caused by eating contaminated food, particularly deli meats, soft cheeses, unpasteurized dairy, or raw vegetables. The bacteria can spread through the bloodstream and potentially affect the brain, spinal cord, or developing babies in pregnant women. Symptoms vary widely—some people experience only mild flu-like illness with fever and muscle aches, while others develop severe complications like meningitis (brain inflammation) or blood poisoning.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, hospitalists, and emergency medicine doctors commonly diagnose and treat listeriosis, typically in hospital or ER settings since it often requires IV antibiotics. Primary care physicians may also encounter this diagnosis, particularly in immunocompromised patients, pregnant women, or elderly populations at higher risk. This code may appear on EOB statements associated with hospital admissions, lab work, or imaging studies rather than routine office visits.",
