    "rawCode": "A33",
    "shortDesc": "Tetanus neonatorum",
    "longDesc": "Tetanus neonatorum",
    "plainEnglish": "Tetanus neonatorum is a serious bacterial infection that occurs in newborn babies, typically within the first two weeks of life. It is caused by the bacterium Clostridium tetani, which usually enters the baby's body through an infected umbilical cord stump—especially when the cord is cut with unsterile instruments or cared for in unsanitary conditions. Affected infants develop severe muscle rigidity and painful spasms, difficulty feeding, and a characteristic jaw clenching (called 'lockjaw'), and without treatment can suffer respiratory failure and death.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, neonatologists, and obstetricians diagnose and treat this code, typically in hospital settings (delivery rooms, neonatal intensive care units, or emergency departments) in regions with poor sanitation or limited access to tetanus vaccination. While rare in developed countries due to routine maternal tetanus vaccination, this code appears on EOBs for affected newborns and is reportable as a serious communicable disease.",
