    "longDesc": "Obstetrical tetanus",
    "plainEnglish": "Obstetrical tetanus is a serious bacterial infection that develops in a woman during pregnancy, childbirth, or the postpartum period when the bacterium Clostridium tetani enters the body through wounds (often from non-sterile delivery conditions or contaminated instruments). The infection causes muscle rigidity, painful spasms, and a characteristic 'lockjaw' where the jaw muscles become so tight the person cannot open their mouth, along with severe muscle contractions throughout the body that can affect breathing. This is a life-threatening condition, but it is now extremely rare in developed countries due to routine tetanus vaccination and modern sterile obstetrical practices.",
    "whoUses": "Obstetricians, gynecologists, and maternal-fetal medicine specialists use this code during pregnancy, labor, and delivery care, as well as in hospital settings when complications arise. It may also appear on EOB statements related to hospitalization, emergency care, or intensive care management during the postpartum period, particularly in cases where urgent intervention is needed to treat the infection.",
