    "rawCode": "A35",
    "shortDesc": "Other tetanus",
    "longDesc": "Other tetanus",
    "plainEnglish": "Tetanus is a serious bacterial infection caused by Clostridium tetani, a bacterium that produces a powerful toxin affecting the nervous system. This toxin causes severe muscle stiffness and painful, involuntary contractions throughout the body—most famously resulting in a clenched jaw (lockjaw), rigid facial expressions, and arched back. The condition develops when the bacteria enters the body through cuts, wounds, or injuries, and while it's now rare in vaccinated populations, it remains life-threatening without prompt medical treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, infectious disease specialists, and intensive care doctors commonly diagnose and treat tetanus in emergency departments and ICU settings. This code typically appears on hospital bills and EOB statements for acute tetanus cases requiring hospitalization, as tetanus requires immediate inpatient care, antitoxin administration, antibiotics, and mechanical ventilation support.",
