    "shortDesc": "Whooping cough due to Bordetella parapertussis w/o pneumonia",
    "longDesc": "Whooping cough due to Bordetella parapertussis without pneumonia",
    "plainEnglish": "Whooping cough caused by a specific bacterium called Bordetella parapertussis is a highly contagious respiratory infection that causes severe coughing fits followed by a distinctive 'whooping' sound when the person tries to breathe in. Unlike the more common type caused by Bordetella pertussis, this version tends to be somewhat milder, and in this case, the infection has NOT spread to or affected the lungs (no pneumonia). The patient experiences prolonged coughing episodes, may vomit after coughing, and can feel extremely exhausted, but their lungs themselves are not infected.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians and family medicine doctors commonly use this code during office visits or urgent care evaluations when diagnosing whooping cough in children or adults. It may also be used in emergency departments when patients present with severe coughing symptoms. This code appears on EOB statements as documentation of the specific cause of the infection for insurance and medical record purposes.",
