    "plainEnglish": "Scarlet fever is a bacterial infection caused by streptococcus bacteria (the same germ that causes strep throat) that produces a distinctive sandpaper-like rash covering the body, along with fever and sore throat. In this case, the patient also has otitis media, which means the infection has spread to or accompanied by inflammation in the middle ear—the space behind the eardrum—causing ear pain, fluid buildup, and sometimes temporary hearing loss. This combination is most common in children and was more serious before antibiotics became available, though it still requires prompt treatment to prevent complications.",
