    "shortDesc": "Scarlet fever, uncomplicated",
    "longDesc": "Scarlet fever, uncomplicated",
    "plainEnglish": "Scarlet fever is a bacterial infection caused by group A streptococcus (the same bacteria that causes strep throat) that spreads through the bloodstream and produces a distinctive bright red, sandpaper-like rash covering much of the body. The condition typically starts with a sore throat, fever, and swollen tonsils, followed by the characteristic rash that appears 1-2 days later, often with a bright red tongue (sometimes called 'strawberry tongue'). 'Uncomplicated' means the infection hasn't led to serious complications like rheumatic fever or kidney damage.",
