    "shortDesc": "Meningococcal meningitis",
    "longDesc": "Meningococcal meningitis",
    "plainEnglish": "Meningococcal meningitis is a serious bacterial infection caused by a germ called Neisseria meningitidis that inflames the protective membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord. The infection spreads through respiratory droplets (like coughing or sneezing) and causes sudden symptoms including severe headache, high fever, stiff neck, sensitivity to light, and sometimes a rash. This is a medical emergency requiring immediate hospitalization and antibiotic treatment, as it can be life-threatening if not treated quickly.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, infectious disease specialists, and hospitalists commonly diagnose and treat meningococcal meningitis in emergency departments and intensive care units. This code appears on hospital bills, ER visit statements, and patient EOBs when someone is admitted with suspected or confirmed meningococcal infection.",
