    "rawCode": "A391",
    "shortDesc": "Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome is a life-threatening bacterial infection (usually caused by meningococcus bacteria) that causes sudden, severe bleeding into the adrenal glands—two small hormone-producing glands that sit on top of the kidneys. This leads to rapid collapse of the body's ability to regulate blood pressure and stress hormones, causing shock, widespread bleeding under the skin (purple/black spots), and organ failure. It develops extremely quickly, often within hours, and is a medical emergency requiring immediate treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, intensive care unit (ICU) specialists, and infectious disease doctors use this code when treating patients presenting to the ER or admitted with acute meningococcal sepsis complicated by adrenal hemorrhage. This code typically appears in hospital inpatient records rather than routine office visit EOB statements due to the acute, critical nature of the condition, though it may appear on hospital bills and insurance explanations of benefits.",
