    "shortDesc": "Acute meningococcemia",
    "longDesc": "Acute meningococcemia",
    "plainEnglish": "Acute meningococcemia is a serious bloodstream infection caused by Neisseria meningitidis bacteria that occurs suddenly and spreads rapidly throughout the body. Unlike meningitis (which primarily affects the brain and spinal cord membranes), this condition involves the bacteria multiplying in the blood itself, causing fever, chills, shock, and sometimes a distinctive purple or dark red rash on the skin. Without immediate treatment with antibiotics, this infection can lead to organ failure and death within hours.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, intensive care specialists, and infectious disease doctors typically diagnose and manage acute meningococcemia in emergency departments and ICUs. This code appears on EOB statements when patients require urgent hospitalization, blood cultures, or IV antibiotic therapy for what is considered a medical emergency requiring immediate intervention.",
