    "rawCode": "A393",
    "shortDesc": "Chronic meningococcemia",
    "longDesc": "Chronic meningococcemia",
    "plainEnglish": "Chronic meningococcemia is a long-lasting bloodstream infection caused by the meningococcus bacteria (Neisseria meningitidis). Unlike the acute form that strikes suddenly, this version develops slowly over weeks or months, causing recurring fever, joint pain, rashes that come and go, and general malaise. The infection persists because the body's immune system hasn't fully cleared the bacteria from the blood, leaving the person vulnerable to complications affecting the heart, joints, and skin.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists and internal medicine physicians typically diagnose and manage chronic meningococcemia, usually through hospital admission or outpatient clinic visits for blood cultures and prolonged antibiotic therapy. This code appears on EOB statements when patients require extended treatment, and may also be used by emergency department providers if the patient presents with acute symptoms during the chronic phase.",
