    "code": "A39.4",
    "rawCode": "A394",
    "shortDesc": "Meningococcemia, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Meningococcemia, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Meningococcemia is a serious bloodstream infection caused by bacteria called Neisseria meningitidis. These bacteria multiply in the blood and can spread throughout the body, causing symptoms like fever, chills, rash (often purple or dark spots), and severe illness. This condition is life-threatening and requires emergency treatment with antibiotics; it can lead to septic shock, organ damage, or meningitis (infection of the membranes around the brain and spinal cord).",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, infectious disease specialists, and intensivists commonly use this code in hospital emergency departments and intensive care units (ICUs). It typically appears on patient EOB statements for hospitalized patients with severe systemic infections requiring urgent intervention.",
