    "shortDesc": "Meningococcal endocarditis",
    "longDesc": "Meningococcal endocarditis",
    "plainEnglish": "Meningococcal endocarditis is a serious infection of the inner lining of the heart (called the endocardium) caused by the bacterium Neisseria meningitidis. This same bacterium is known for causing meningitis, but in this case it has entered the bloodstream and settled in the heart, where it causes inflammation and damage to the heart valves. Patients typically experience fever, heart murmurs, shortness of breath, and may develop heart failure if not treated promptly with antibiotics.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, cardiologists, and emergency medicine physicians commonly use this code when diagnosing and treating patients with this life-threatening infection. It typically appears in acute care hospital settings (ER or ICU) and may be noted on patient EOB statements as part of hospitalization claims for severe sepsis or endocarditis requiring IV antibiotics and possible cardiac surgery.",
