    "shortDesc": "Meningococcal myocarditis",
    "longDesc": "Meningococcal myocarditis",
    "plainEnglish": "Meningococcal myocarditis is a serious infection of the heart muscle caused by the bacterium Neisseria meningitidis, the same organism that causes bacterial meningitis. This condition causes inflammation and damage to the myocardium (the thick muscular layer of the heart), which can lead to heart weakness, irregular heartbeats, and potentially life-threatening heart failure. Patients typically experience chest pain, shortness of breath, fatigue, and may show signs of shock or organ failure during the acute infection.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by infectious disease specialists, cardiologists, and emergency medicine physicians, typically in hospitalized or critically ill patients presenting with meningococcal sepsis. It commonly appears in intensive care unit (ICU) settings, emergency departments, and on hospital bills rather than routine office visit EOBs, as this is a severe, often life-threatening condition requiring immediate hospitalization and aggressive treatment.",
