    "code": "A39.81",
    "rawCode": "A3981",
    "shortDesc": "Meningococcal encephalitis",
    "longDesc": "Meningococcal encephalitis",
    "plainEnglish": "Meningococcal encephalitis is a serious brain infection caused by the bacterium Neisseria meningitidis. Unlike meningitis, which inflames the protective membranes around the brain and spinal cord, encephalitis specifically involves inflammation of the brain tissue itself. Patients typically experience high fever, severe headache, confusion, seizures, altered consciousness, and sometimes stiff neck, and this condition requires emergency treatment with antibiotics to prevent permanent brain damage or death.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, infectious disease specialists, intensivists, and neurologists commonly diagnose and treat this condition in emergency departments and intensive care units. This code frequently appears on hospital bills and insurance EOBs as it represents a critical, life-threatening infection requiring hospitalization and aggressive antibiotic therapy.",
