    "shortDesc": "Meningococcal retrobulbar neuritis",
    "longDesc": "Meningococcal retrobulbar neuritis",
    "plainEnglish": "Meningococcal retrobulbar neuritis is an infection of the optic nerve (the nerve behind the eye that carries vision signals to the brain) caused by the meningococcus bacterium. This condition causes inflammation and damage to the nerve tissue located behind the eyeball, resulting in vision problems such as blurred vision, pain with eye movement, or loss of color vision. It's a serious complication of meningococcal disease that requires prompt antibiotic treatment to prevent permanent vision loss.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, neurologists, and ophthalmologists typically use this code when treating patients with meningococcal infections that have spread to affect the optic nerve. It's commonly documented in hospital settings, emergency departments, or specialized infectious disease clinics, and may appear on EOB statements for patients hospitalized with complicated meningococcal disease requiring intensive care and imaging studies.",
