    "plainEnglish": "Meningococcal arthritis is a joint infection caused by bacteria called Neisseria meningitidis, the same bacteria that causes meningitis (infection of the membranes around the brain and spinal cord). This bacterial infection spreads through the bloodstream and settles in one or more joints, causing them to become painfully swollen, warm, and stiff. Patients typically experience severe joint pain, fever, and difficulty moving the affected joint, and this is a serious medical emergency requiring immediate treatment with antibiotics to prevent permanent joint damage.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and rheumatologists commonly diagnose and treat meningococcal arthritis in hospital settings, urgent care, or emergency departments. This code frequently appears on EOB statements for hospitalized patients and is important for insurance documentation of a serious bacterial infection requiring intensive care and IV antibiotic therapy.",
