    "plainEnglish": "Group A Streptococcus sepsis is a severe, life-threatening bloodstream infection caused by Group A Streptococcus bacteria (the same bacteria that causes strep throat). The infection spreads from its source—often the throat, skin, or a wound—into the blood and can rapidly damage multiple organs throughout the body. Patients typically experience sudden high fever, chills, confusion, rapid heartbeat, low blood pressure, and sometimes a rash, and this condition requires emergency hospital treatment with antibiotics.",
