    "shortDesc": "Sepsis due to Enterococcus",
    "longDesc": "Sepsis due to Enterococcus",
    "plainEnglish": "Sepsis due to Enterococcus is a serious bloodstream infection caused by enterococcus bacteria, which normally live harmlessly in your gut but can cause life-threatening infection when they enter the blood. This typically happens after surgery, through medical devices like catheters, or in people with weakened immune systems. Patients experience fever, chills, rapid heartbeat, low blood pressure, and signs of organ dysfunction, which requires immediate hospital treatment with antibiotics.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by emergency medicine physicians, intensivists in ICUs, infectious disease specialists, and hospitalists when treating patients with confirmed enterococcal bloodstream infection. It commonly appears on hospital bills and insurance EOBs as a complication diagnosis during inpatient stays, often accompanying procedure codes for sepsis management, and is important for tracking hospital-acquired infections.",
