    "code": "A41.89",
    "rawCode": "A4189",
    "shortDesc": "Other specified sepsis",
    "longDesc": "Other specified sepsis",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes sepsis—a life-threatening condition where an infection (from bacteria, fungi, or other germs) spreads through the bloodstream and triggers a severe whole-body inflammatory response that can damage organs and lead to shock. Unlike sepsis from a known specific source (like pneumonia or urinary tract infection), this code is used when the type of sepsis is known but doesn't fit into other more specific categories, or when the exact organism isn't clearly identified. Patients typically experience fever, rapid heartbeat, rapid breathing, confusion, and may have low blood pressure or organ dysfunction.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, hospitalists, and intensive care specialists commonly use this code when admitting critically ill patients to the ICU or emergency department. This code frequently appears on hospital bills and EOB statements as sepsis is a serious, expensive condition requiring extensive monitoring and treatment. It's also used by infectious disease specialists and surgical teams when managing post-operative or post-procedural sepsis.",
