    "longDesc": "Sepsis, unspecified organism",
    "plainEnglish": "Sepsis is a life-threatening condition where your body has an extreme reaction to an infection, causing widespread inflammation and organ dysfunction. When doctors cannot identify the specific bacteria, virus, or fungus causing the infection, they code it as \"unspecified organism\" sepsis. You may experience fever, rapid heart rate, breathing difficulty, confusion, and dangerously low blood pressure if sepsis develops.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, intensivists, and hospitalists use this code when a patient is admitted with sepsis but the causative organism hasn't been identified yet—often at initial presentation before culture results return. It commonly appears on hospital bills and insurance EOB statements since sepsis requires urgent hospitalization and intensive care.",
