    "longDesc": "Pulmonary actinomycosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Pulmonary actinomycosis is a rare bacterial infection of the lungs caused by Actinomyces, bacteria that normally live harmlessly in the mouth and throat but can cause disease if they get into the lungs, usually after aspiration or injury. The infection causes chronic inflammation and scarring in the lungs, leading to symptoms like persistent cough, chest pain, fever, and sometimes coughing up blood or pus. It develops slowly over weeks to months and can form abscesses or draining sinuses if left untreated.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonologists, infectious disease specialists, and emergency medicine physicians commonly diagnose and treat this condition, typically during evaluation of chronic respiratory symptoms in office visits, urgent care, or hospitalization. This code appears on patient EOBs when actinomycosis is confirmed through imaging, sputum cultures, or bronchoscopy and requires prolonged antibiotic therapy.",
