    "shortDesc": "Abdominal actinomycosis",
    "longDesc": "Abdominal actinomycosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Abdominal actinomycosis is a rare bacterial infection caused by Actinomyces bacteria (normally found in your mouth and gut) that has spread into the abdominal cavity and internal organs like the intestines or liver. The infection typically develops slowly over weeks or months and causes persistent abdominal pain, swelling, fever, and sometimes draining sinuses (tunnels under the skin that leak pus). It usually occurs after surgery, trauma, or perforation of the intestines that allows the bacteria to escape into the sterile abdominal space.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, gastroenterologists, and general surgeons commonly diagnose and treat abdominal actinomycosis, typically in hospital or surgical settings after imaging findings suggest the condition. This code appears on EOB statements when patients require hospitalization, imaging studies, or surgical intervention for confirmed or suspected actinomycosis, though the condition is rare enough that many primary care providers will refer to specialists before coding it.",
