    "plainEnglish": "Cervicofacial actinomycosis is a chronic bacterial infection caused by Actinomyces bacteria that affects the jaw, neck, and face. It typically develops after dental work, tooth extractions, or injuries to the mouth and jaw area, allowing the normally harmless bacteria in your mouth to invade deeper tissues. The infection causes painful swelling and abscess formation in the jaw and neck, often with draining sores and a hard, lumpy appearance sometimes called \"lumpy jaw.\"",
    "whoUses": "Dentists, oral surgeons, and ENT specialists commonly diagnose and treat cervicofacial actinomycosis, typically in office or surgical settings following dental procedures or trauma. This code may appear on EOB statements for patients requiring dental consultations, imaging (CT/MRI), drainage procedures, or prolonged antibiotic therapy.",
