    "shortDesc": "Actinomycotic sepsis",
    "longDesc": "Actinomycotic sepsis",
    "plainEnglish": "Actinomycotic sepsis is a serious bloodstream infection caused by Actinomyces bacteria, which are normally found in the mouth and gut but can spread throughout the body when the skin or tissue barrier is broken. When these bacteria multiply in the blood, they trigger a severe systemic infection that can cause fever, chills, weakness, and organ dysfunction. This is a rare but dangerous condition that requires aggressive antibiotic treatment because the infection has escaped a localized area and is now traveling through the bloodstream.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists when managing sepsis cases in acute hospital settings, particularly in the ICU. It may also appear on EOB statements for hospitalized patients, though it is relatively uncommon since actinomycosis itself is a rare infection in developed countries.",
