    "longDesc": "Pulmonary nocardiosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Pulmonary nocardiosis is a serious lung infection caused by bacteria called Nocardia, which are found in soil and water. The infection develops when a person inhales dust or debris containing these bacteria, and it primarily affects the lungs but can sometimes spread to other parts of the body. Symptoms include persistent cough, chest pain, fever, and shortness of breath that may develop gradually over weeks or months.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonary infectious disease specialists, pulmonologists, and emergency medicine physicians commonly diagnose and treat this condition, typically in hospital settings or through hospitalization since it requires prolonged antibiotic therapy. This code appears on EOB statements for patients hospitalized with respiratory infections or those with weakened immune systems (such as HIV/AIDS or organ transplant recipients) who develop this opportunistic infection.",
