    "code": "A44.1",
    "rawCode": "A441",
    "shortDesc": "Cutaneous and mucocutaneous bartonellosis",
    "longDesc": "Cutaneous and mucocutaneous bartonellosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Cutaneous and mucocutaneous bartonellosis is a bacterial skin infection caused by Bartonella species (most commonly Bartonella bacilliformis), typically transmitted by sandflies in tropical and subtropical regions. The infection causes red or purple bumpy lesions on the skin and sores inside the mouth or on mucous membranes, which can be painful and may last for weeks to months if untreated. This condition is sometimes called \"verruga peruana\" or wart fever and is different from the more serious systemic form of bartonellosis that affects internal organs.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by infectious disease specialists, dermatologists, and travel medicine physicians when evaluating patients with characteristic skin lesions and a history of travel to endemic areas (mainly the Andes region of South America). It typically appears in office visits, urgent care settings, or dermatology consultations, and may show up on patient EOB statements when antibiotics are prescribed to treat the infection.",
