    "longDesc": "Other forms of bartonellosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Bartonellosis is an infection caused by bacteria called Bartonella that spread through insect bites, typically from sand flies or lice. This code represents less common or atypical forms of the infection that don't fit the standard presentations. Symptoms can vary widely but may include fever, fatigue, skin lesions, swollen lymph nodes, or in severe cases, inflammation of the heart valves or bone pain.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, tropical medicine doctors, and emergency medicine physicians use this code when diagnosing unusual presentations of Bartonella infection, particularly in patients with travel history to endemic regions or unexplained fever with compatible symptoms. This code may appear on EOB statements for patients seen in specialty clinics, urgent care, or hospital settings for evaluation and treatment of suspected atypical bartonellosis.",
