    "code": "A46",
    "rawCode": "A46",
    "shortDesc": "Erysipelas",
    "longDesc": "Erysipelas",
    "plainEnglish": "Erysipelas is a bacterial skin infection caused by Group A Streptococcus (the same bacteria that causes strep throat) that spreads through the upper layers of skin and nearby lymph nodes. The affected skin becomes red, swollen, warm, and often has a distinctive raised border that looks like it's been drawn with a marker; patients typically experience fever, chills, and flu-like symptoms along with the skin changes. This infection most commonly appears on the face or lower legs and can develop rapidly over hours or days.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, emergency medicine doctors, and dermatologists commonly diagnose and treat erysipelas in outpatient, urgent care, or emergency department settings. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements since erysipelas requires prompt antibiotic treatment and may involve multiple office visits or ER evaluations to monitor response to therapy.",
