    "shortDesc": "Gas gangrene",
    "longDesc": "Gas gangrene",
    "plainEnglish": "Gas gangrene is a life-threatening bacterial infection that causes tissue death and the formation of gas bubbles in muscle and surrounding tissues, typically following an injury or wound contamination. The infection spreads rapidly and painfully, causing severe swelling, discoloration of the skin, and systemic illness. If left untreated, it can lead to sepsis, organ failure, and death, making it a medical emergency requiring immediate hospitalization and often surgical removal of affected tissue.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by emergency medicine physicians, trauma surgeons, infectious disease specialists, and general surgeons in hospital emergency departments and operating rooms when treating acute wound infections or traumatic injuries. It commonly appears on hospital bills and EOB statements for patients requiring urgent surgical debridement, antibiotics, and intensive care management.",
