    "rawCode": "A481",
    "shortDesc": "Legionnaires' disease",
    "longDesc": "Legionnaires' disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Legionnaires' disease is a serious lung infection caused by bacteria called Legionella that grows in warm water systems like air conditioners, hot tubs, and fountains. People typically get infected by breathing in contaminated water droplets in the air rather than by drinking water. The illness causes high fever, severe cough, chest pain, shortness of breath, and sometimes confusion or kidney problems, often developing 2-10 days after exposure.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonologists, infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists commonly use this code when diagnosing patients with severe pneumonia symptoms and confirmed Legionella infection, typically in hospital or emergency department settings. This code frequently appears on EOB statements for patients requiring hospitalization, as Legionnaires' disease often requires IV antibiotics and intensive care monitoring.",
