    "longDesc": "Nonpneumonic Legionnaires' disease [Pontiac fever]",
    "plainEnglish": "Pontiac fever is a milder form of Legionnaires' disease caused by breathing in bacteria (Legionella) from contaminated water sources like air conditioning systems, hot tubs, or fountains. Unlike the more serious pneumonic form that affects the lungs, Pontiac fever causes flu-like symptoms such as fever, muscle aches, headache, and fatigue that typically develop within 1-2 days of exposure and usually resolve within a week without causing pneumonia.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, infectious disease specialists, and primary care doctors commonly use this code when patients present with acute respiratory illness suspected to be Legionella infection, typically in urgent care or emergency department settings. This code may appear on EOB statements for patients hospitalized or treated in the ER for suspected or confirmed Legionella exposure, particularly during outbreaks linked to contaminated water systems.",
