    "rawCode": "A483",
    "shortDesc": "Toxic shock syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Toxic shock syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Toxic shock syndrome (TSS) is a rare but serious, life-threatening infection caused by bacteria (usually Staphylococcus aureus or Streptococcus pyogenes) that release harmful toxins into the bloodstream. The condition develops rapidly and causes the body's immune system to go into overdrive, leading to symptoms like high fever, rash, low blood pressure, organ failure, and shock. It requires immediate emergency treatment with antibiotics and supportive care, as it can be fatal if not treated quickly.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, intensivists (ICU doctors), and infectious disease specialists most commonly diagnose and treat toxic shock syndrome in emergency departments and intensive care units. This code appears on patient EOBs for hospital admissions and emergency care, and while historically associated with tampon use, it can occur after any bacterial infection including wounds, surgery, or childbirth.",
