    "shortDesc": "Brazilian purpuric fever",
    "longDesc": "Brazilian purpuric fever",
    "plainEnglish": "Brazilian purpuric fever is a rare and serious bacterial infection caused by a specific strain of Haemophilus influenzae that primarily affects children in Brazil and a few other regions. The disease causes high fever, purple or dark red skin rashes (purpura), and can lead to severe complications like shock and organ failure if not treated promptly with antibiotics. It often spreads through contact with contaminated water or infected individuals and develops very quickly, making it a medical emergency.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, pediatricians, and emergency medicine physicians use this code, typically in hospital or emergency department settings in endemic regions or when a child presents with unexplained fever and purpura. This code rarely appears on patient EOB statements in non-endemic countries but may be used for diagnosis documentation in international travel medicine or when imported cases occur.",
