    "shortDesc": "Wound botulism",
    "longDesc": "Wound botulism",
    "plainEnglish": "Wound botulism is a rare but serious infection that occurs when botulism bacteria (Clostridium botulinum) contaminate an open wound and produce a toxin in the body. Unlike food poisoning botulism, this type develops directly from bacteria living in a wound rather than from eating contaminated food. The toxin blocks nerve signals to muscles, causing progressive weakness, drooping eyelids, difficulty swallowing, and potentially life-threatening paralysis of the breathing muscles.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, infectious disease specialists, and critical care intensivists typically diagnose and manage wound botulism in hospital or ICU settings. This code is commonly used during acute hospitalization for wound management and antitoxin treatment, and may appear on EOB statements for patients requiring extended intensive care or mechanical ventilation due to respiratory paralysis.",
