    "longDesc": "Methicillin susceptible Staphylococcus aureus infection, unspecified site",
    "plainEnglish": "This code means you have a bacterial infection caused by Staphylococcus aureus (a common skin bacterium) somewhere in your body, but the doctor hasn't pinpointed the exact location of the infection. The good news is that this particular strain of staph bacteria responds well to standard antibiotics like methicillin or penicillin, making it easier to treat than drug-resistant staph. Symptoms depend on where the infection is—it could be a skin sore, a wound infection, or a more serious internal infection causing fever and pain.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency room doctors, urgent care clinics, hospital inpatient teams, and primary care physicians commonly use this code when a patient has lab-confirmed staph infection but the specific site hasn't been identified yet. It often appears as an initial diagnosis code in ERs or during hospital admission workups before the infection's location is determined. This code frequently shows up on patient EOB statements from hospital and lab claims.",
