    "code": "A51.31",
    "rawCode": "A5131",
    "shortDesc": "Condyloma latum",
    "longDesc": "Condyloma latum",
    "plainEnglish": "Condyloma latum is a highly contagious skin lesion caused by secondary syphilis, a sexually transmitted infection. These are flat, moist, wart-like growths that typically appear in warm, moist areas of the body (such as the genital area, armpits, or around the mouth) and are teeming with bacteria, making them extremely infectious to sexual partners. The condition develops weeks to months after the initial syphilis infection and signals that the disease has spread throughout the body.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, dermatologists, and sexual health clinics commonly diagnose and treat condyloma latum during office visits or sexual health screenings. This code appears in hospital settings when patients present with secondary syphilis complications. It typically appears on EOB statements for patients with diagnosed syphilis requiring treatment and partner notification.",
