    "shortDesc": "Syphilitic alopecia",
    "longDesc": "Syphilitic alopecia",
    "plainEnglish": "Syphilitic alopecia is hair loss that occurs as a result of untreated or late-stage syphilis, a sexually transmitted bacterial infection caused by Treponema pallidum. When syphilis progresses, it can damage hair follicles and cause patchy or diffuse hair loss on the scalp, eyebrows, or other body areas. This type of hair loss is relatively uncommon today but represents a sign that syphilis has progressed beyond its early stages and requires immediate antibiotic treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists, infectious disease specialists, and primary care physicians may use this code when evaluating a patient with hair loss and confirmed syphilis diagnosis. It typically appears in office visits or specialty consultations focused on skin manifestations of systemic infection. This code may appear on patient EOB statements when hair loss is being evaluated in the context of syphilis treatment.",
