    "code": "A51.39",
    "rawCode": "A5139",
    "shortDesc": "Other secondary syphilis of skin",
    "longDesc": "Other secondary syphilis of skin",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes various skin rashes and lesions caused by secondary syphilis, a sexually transmitted infection caused by the bacterium Treponema pallidum. Secondary syphilis occurs weeks to months after the initial infection and can cause widespread skin manifestations beyond the common syphilitic rash (exanthem), including pustules, ulcers, or other abnormal skin conditions. These skin findings indicate the infection has spread throughout the body and requires prompt antibiotic treatment to prevent serious long-term complications.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, dermatologists, and primary care physicians commonly use this code when diagnosing and treating secondary syphilis in office visits, urgent care, or sexually transmitted infection (STI) clinics. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements and medical records when syphilis testing is positive and skin manifestations are documented during evaluation.",
