    "code": "A51.41",
    "rawCode": "A5141",
    "shortDesc": "Secondary syphilitic meningitis",
    "longDesc": "Secondary syphilitic meningitis",
    "plainEnglish": "Secondary syphilitic meningitis is a serious infection of the fluid and membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord caused by untreated or incompletely treated syphilis. This occurs when the syphilis bacteria (Treponema pallidum) spreads to the central nervous system weeks to months after the initial infection, causing inflammation of the protective membranes around the brain and spinal cord. Patients typically experience severe headache, stiff neck, fever, sensitivity to light, and sometimes confusion or altered consciousness.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, neurologists, and emergency medicine physicians commonly diagnose and treat this condition, typically in hospital or emergency department settings. This code may appear on EOB statements for patients hospitalized with meningitis symptoms who test positive for syphilis, particularly in cases where the patient had delayed or no treatment for primary or secondary syphilis.",
