    "shortDesc": "Secondary syphilitic oculopathy",
    "longDesc": "Secondary syphilitic oculopathy",
    "plainEnglish": "Secondary syphilitic oculopathy is an eye infection caused by untreated syphilis bacteria that has spread to the eyes during the second stage of the disease. This typically occurs weeks to months after the initial infection and can cause inflammation, blurred vision, eye pain, and light sensitivity. The infection can affect different parts of the eye including the uvea (the colored part), the retina (the light-sensing layer), or the optic nerve, potentially leading to vision problems if not treated with antibiotics.",
    "whoUses": "Ophthalmologists and infectious disease specialists commonly use this code when evaluating patients with eye inflammation related to secondary syphilis, typically during office visits or specialty consultations triggered by vision complaints. The code may appear on EOB statements for patients undergoing eye exams, imaging, or treatment for syphilis-related eye complications in both outpatient and hospital settings.",
