    "rawCode": "A5144",
    "shortDesc": "Secondary syphilitic nephritis",
    "longDesc": "Secondary syphilitic nephritis",
    "plainEnglish": "Secondary syphilitic nephritis is kidney inflammation caused by syphilis infection that has progressed beyond the initial stage. Syphilis is a sexually transmitted bacterial infection, and when it spreads through the bloodstream during the secondary phase (typically weeks to months after infection), it can damage the kidneys, causing them to become inflamed and potentially leak protein into the urine or reduce kidney function. Patients may experience symptoms like swelling in the legs and face, dark urine, or foamy urine, though some people may not notice obvious signs until kidney damage is more advanced.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by infectious disease specialists, nephrologists (kidney doctors), and primary care physicians in outpatient clinics, urgent care settings, or hospital admissions when syphilis is diagnosed with concurrent kidney involvement. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements when the patient undergoes urine testing, blood work, or kidney function monitoring during treatment of secondary syphilis.",
