    "shortDesc": "Secondary syphilitic hepatitis",
    "longDesc": "Secondary syphilitic hepatitis",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means a person has liver inflammation caused by secondary syphilis, which is a sexually transmitted infection caused by the bacterium Treponema pallidum. Secondary syphilis occurs weeks to months after the initial infection and can spread throughout the body, affecting multiple organs including the liver. When the infection damages the liver, it causes inflammation (hepatitis), which can lead to symptoms like jaundice (yellowing of skin and eyes), abdominal pain, and elevated liver enzymes on blood tests.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by infectious disease specialists, primary care physicians, hepatologists, and emergency medicine doctors when evaluating or treating patients with secondary syphilis who have liver involvement. It's typically used in office visits, urgent care settings, or hospital admissions when liver disease is documented alongside confirmed secondary syphilis. This code may appear on patient EOBs, particularly if the patient is being treated with antibiotics and undergoing liver function monitoring.",
