    "code": "A52.01",
    "rawCode": "A5201",
    "shortDesc": "Syphilitic aneurysm of aorta",
    "longDesc": "Syphilitic aneurysm of aorta",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis describes a weakening and ballooning of the aorta (your body's largest blood vessel) caused by untreated syphilis. When syphilis bacteria spread through the bloodstream over months or years, they can damage the aorta's walls, causing them to become thin and stretched. This creates a dangerous bulge (aneurysm) that could rupture and cause life-threatening bleeding, though it may cause no symptoms until it becomes critical.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, vascular surgeons, and infectious disease specialists most commonly use this code when diagnosing and treating late-stage syphilis complications, typically during imaging studies (CT or ultrasound), hospital admissions, or surgical consultations. This code frequently appears on hospital bills and EOB statements since management often requires imaging, specialist consultations, and possibly surgery.",
