    "rawCode": "A5202",
    "shortDesc": "Syphilitic aortitis",
    "longDesc": "Syphilitic aortitis",
    "plainEnglish": "Syphilitic aortitis is a serious infection of the aorta—the large blood vessel that carries blood from the heart to the rest of the body—caused by untreated syphilis. When syphilis bacteria (spirochetes) spread to the aorta over time, they inflame and damage the vessel wall, which can weaken it and lead to dangerous complications like aneurysms (bulging) or rupture. Patients may experience chest pain, shortness of breath, or have no symptoms at all until a serious complication occurs.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, infectious disease specialists, and vascular surgeons use this code when diagnosing and treating syphilis complications affecting the heart and major blood vessels, typically in hospitalized or advanced outpatient settings. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients with late-stage syphilis requiring imaging (CT/echocardiography), antibiotics, and potentially surgical intervention.",
