    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis describes brain and blood vessel damage caused by untreated syphilis, a sexually transmitted bacterial infection that has progressed to affect the nervous system. When syphilis goes untreated for years, the bacteria can damage the arteries and tissues in the brain, potentially causing stroke-like symptoms, weakness, numbness, or cognitive changes. This is a late-stage complication of syphilis that occurs months or years after the initial infection.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, neurologists, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing neurosyphilis in patients with a history of untreated syphilis and current neurological symptoms. It typically appears in hospital settings, specialty clinics, or emergency departments when a patient presents with stroke symptoms or neurological decline and syphilis testing is positive. This code is commonly seen on EOB statements for patients requiring hospitalization, imaging studies, or specialist consultations related to late-stage syphilis complications.",
