    "shortDesc": "Tabes dorsalis",
    "longDesc": "Tabes dorsalis",
    "plainEnglish": "Tabes dorsalis is a late-stage complication of syphilis that develops years or decades after the initial infection, even if the disease was never treated or treatment was inadequate. This condition damages the nerve fibers in the spinal cord that carry pain and temperature sensations, as well as those that control coordination and balance. Patients typically experience severe shooting pains (especially in the legs), loss of balance and coordination, progressive weakness, and eventually partial paralysis—all caused by slow degeneration of nerve tissue rather than active infection.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, infectious disease specialists, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing or managing neurosyphilis in patients with a history of untreated or inadequately treated syphilis. This code typically appears in hospital settings, specialty clinics, and sometimes in office-based evaluations, and is commonly seen on EOB statements as it indicates a serious chronic neurological condition requiring ongoing care.",
