    "plainEnglish": "Syphilis is a serious sexually transmitted infection caused by a bacterium called spirochete that spreads through direct contact with syphilitic sores (usually during sexual contact) or from mother to baby during pregnancy. When a patient is diagnosed with syphilis but the doctor hasn't yet determined which stage of the disease they're in—or the stage isn't specified in their medical records—the code A53.9 is used. Symptoms vary widely depending on the stage: early syphilis may cause painless sores or rashes, while untreated syphilis can eventually damage the heart, brain, and other organs over years.",
