    "plainEnglish": "Latent yaws is an inactive stage of yaws, a tropical bacterial infection caused by a spirochete (a spiral-shaped bacterium) that primarily affects the skin and bones. During the latent phase, the infection is present in the body but not causing active symptoms or signs of disease—the person may feel completely normal and appear healthy. This stage can last for years, and without treatment, the infection could potentially reactivate later, though latent yaws itself doesn't cause pain, swelling, or visible lesions.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists and tropical medicine doctors most commonly use this code, typically during follow-up visits or screening of patients with a history of yaws from endemic regions (primarily parts of Africa, South America, and Asia). This code may also appear when primary care physicians in non-endemic countries evaluate patients who were treated for active yaws and are now in remission, though it rarely appears on typical patient EOB statements unless the patient is being seen specifically for infectious disease management.",
