    "shortDesc": "Lyme disease, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Lyme disease, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Lyme disease is a bacterial infection transmitted through tick bites, most commonly from infected deer ticks found in wooded or grassy areas. When the diagnosis is listed as 'unspecified,' it means the patient has been confirmed to have Lyme disease but the specific stage or type hasn't been documented (early localized, early disseminated, or late chronic). Symptoms can include a characteristic bull's-eye rash, fever, joint pain, and fatigue, though some people have few or no obvious symptoms initially.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by primary care physicians, infectious disease specialists, and emergency medicine doctors during office visits, urgent care evaluations, or hospital admissions when Lyme disease is confirmed but the clinical stage is unclear or not yet specified. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements when antibiotics and diagnostic testing (such as Lyme serology) are ordered.",
