    "plainEnglish": "Trachoma is a serious eye infection caused by a bacterium called Chlamydia trachomatis, and A71.0 refers to when someone first develops this disease. In the early stage, the infected person typically experiences eye redness, irritation, discharge, and swollen eyelids, similar to bacterial conjunctivitis (pink eye). If left untreated, trachoma can progress and eventually cause scarring of the cornea and blindness, making early detection and treatment critically important.",
    "whoUses": "Ophthalmologists, optometrists, and primary care physicians commonly use this code when diagnosing trachoma in clinic or office settings, particularly in patients from endemic regions or with travel history to areas where the disease is prevalent. This code would appear on patient EOBs for eye exams, antibiotic treatments, and related ophthalmology visits, though trachoma is rare in developed countries and more commonly seen in resource-limited areas with poor sanitation.",
