    "shortDesc": "Epidemic louse-borne typhus fever d/t Rickettsia prowazekii",
    "longDesc": "Epidemic louse-borne typhus fever due to Rickettsia prowazekii",
    "plainEnglish": "Epidemic louse-borne typhus is a serious bacterial infection spread by body lice that carry a microorganism called Rickettsia prowazekii. The disease typically develops after an infected louse bites a person, and causes high fever, severe headache, muscle aches, and a distinctive rash that usually starts on the trunk and spreads outward. This infection is rare in developed countries today but historically has caused outbreaks in crowded, unsanitary conditions where lice infestations are common.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists when diagnosing and treating patients with confirmed epidemic typhus, typically in an acute care or hospital setting. It may appear on patient EOB statements for those hospitalized with this serious infection, though the condition is uncommon in modern U.S. medical practice and more frequently seen in areas with poor living conditions or during humanitarian crises.",
