    "shortDesc": "Recrudescent typhus [Brill's disease]",
    "longDesc": "Recrudescent typhus [Brill's disease]",
    "plainEnglish": "Recrudescent typhus, also known as Brill's disease, is a bacterial infection that resurfaces in someone who previously had epidemic typhus (louse-borne typhus) years or even decades earlier. The infection is caused by the same bacteria that causes the original typhus, but it comes back when a person's immune system weakens due to stress, aging, or illness. Symptoms include fever, headache, body aches, and rash, typically milder than the original infection.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists and emergency medicine physicians use this code when diagnosing patients with recurrent typhus symptoms, particularly in cases with a known history of previous typhus exposure. This code may appear on EOB statements for patients requiring hospitalization, laboratory testing (serologic confirmation), or antibiotic treatment in hospital or clinic settings.",
