    "code": "A78",
    "rawCode": "A78",
    "shortDesc": "Q fever",
    "longDesc": "Q fever",
    "plainEnglish": "Q fever is a contagious bacterial infection caused by a microorganism called Coxiella burnetii, usually contracted from infected animals like cattle, sheep, or goats—particularly through inhalation of contaminated dust or aerosols from their birth products or body fluids. Most people infected develop flu-like symptoms including fever, fatigue, headache, and muscle aches that typically appear 2–3 weeks after exposure, though some infected people have no symptoms at all. In rare cases, the infection can progress to a chronic form that affects the heart valves or other organs if left untreated.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, primary care physicians, and emergency medicine doctors diagnose and treat Q fever, typically in outpatient or hospital settings based on symptom severity. This code commonly appears on EOB statements when patients undergo testing (blood cultures or serology) or receive antibiotic treatment for confirmed Q fever infection.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
