    "rawCode": "A790",
    "shortDesc": "Trench fever",
    "longDesc": "Trench fever",
    "plainEnglish": "Trench fever is a bacterial infection spread by human body lice that causes repeated episodes of fever, chills, and severe body aches. The infection is caused by a bacterium called Bartonella quintana and historically affected soldiers in crowded, unsanitary conditions (hence the name), though it still occurs today in homeless populations and areas with poor hygiene. Patients typically experience cyclical fevers that come and go, often with muscle pain and fatigue, and the condition can last for weeks or even months if untreated.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, primary care physicians, and emergency medicine doctors diagnose and treat trench fever, typically based on blood tests and patient history of louse exposure. This code appears in clinical settings ranging from urgent care to hospital admission when patients present with unexplained recurring fever, and may show up on EOB statements when laboratory work or specialist consultations are billed for fever of unknown origin investigation.",
