    "shortDesc": "Rickettsialpox due to Rickettsia akari",
    "longDesc": "Rickettsialpox due to Rickettsia akari",
    "plainEnglish": "Rickettsialpox is a rare infectious disease caused by a bacterium called Rickettsia akari, which is transmitted to humans through mites that live on mice and rats. The infection typically causes a rash of small blisters (similar to chickenpox), fever, headache, and muscle aches, usually appearing 1–3 weeks after exposure. Most cases occur in urban areas with mouse infestations and resolve on their own or with antibiotic treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and primary care doctors use this code when diagnosing a patient with confirmed rickettsialpox, typically in an office visit, urgent care, or emergency department setting. This code is less common on patient EOB statements since rickettsialpox is rare, but it may appear when laboratory confirmation of Rickettsia akari is documented during an acute illness evaluation.",
