    "shortDesc": "Rickettsiosis due to Ehrlichia sennetsu",
    "longDesc": "Rickettsiosis due to Ehrlichia sennetsu",
    "plainEnglish": "Sennetsu fever is a rare infectious disease caused by a bacteria called Ehrlichia sennetsu, which is typically transmitted through tick bites. This infection causes flu-like symptoms including fever, chills, headache, muscle aches, and general fatigue, and can occasionally lead to more serious complications affecting the blood and organs if left untreated. It's most commonly found in East Asia, particularly Japan and Southeast Asia.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, primary care physicians, and emergency medicine doctors use this code when diagnosing or treating patients with confirmed Ehrlichia sennetsu infection, typically in office visits, urgent care, or hospital settings. This code occasionally appears on patient EOB statements when testing and treatment for this rickettsia-caused illness are billed, though it is relatively uncommon in most U.S. medical practices.",
