    "rawCode": "A7982",
    "shortDesc": "Anaplasmosis [A. phagocytophilum]",
    "longDesc": "Anaplasmosis [A. phagocytophilum]",
    "plainEnglish": "Anaplasmosis is a rare bacterial infection spread by tick bites, caused by a bacterium called Anaplasma phagocytophilum. When an infected tick bites you, the bacteria enters your bloodstream and attacks certain white blood cells, causing flu-like symptoms such as fever, chills, headache, muscle aches, and fatigue that typically appear within 1–2 weeks of infection. Most cases occur in spring and summer when ticks are active, and the infection can range from mild to severe, especially in older adults or people with weakened immune systems.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine doctors, and primary care physicians commonly diagnose and treat anaplasmosis, typically in urgent care or emergency department settings during tick season. This code appears on patient EOB statements when laboratory testing (blood tests showing characteristic changes) and clinical presentation lead to confirmation of the diagnosis, and it is often coded alongside tick-borne illness encounters.",
