    "shortDesc": "Other specified rickettsioses",
    "longDesc": "Other specified rickettsioses",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a rare infection caused by Rickettsia bacteria—tiny organisms spread through tick, louse, or flea bites—that doesn't fit into the common rickettsial diseases like Rocky Mountain spotted fever or typhus. Symptoms typically include fever, headache, muscle aches, and sometimes a rash, developing days to weeks after an infected insect bite. The specific type of rickettsial infection is unusual or less commonly recognized, so doctors use this code when they've confirmed a rickettsial disease but it doesn't match the standard categories.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine doctors, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing or treating patients with confirmed rickettsia infections that are atypical or rare. It commonly appears in urgent care or ER settings for acutely ill patients and is likely to show up on EOB statements related to emergency evaluation, laboratory testing, or specialist consultations for febrile illnesses.",
