    "shortDesc": "Rickettsiosis, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Rickettsiosis, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Rickettsiosis is a bacterial infection caused by tiny organisms called Rickettsiae that are usually spread to humans through tick, flea, or louse bites. This code is used when a doctor knows the patient has this type of infection but hasn't pinpointed the exact variety (such as Rocky Mountain spotted fever or typhus). Symptoms typically include fever, headache, muscle aches, and sometimes a rash, and the condition requires antibiotic treatment to clear up.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and primary care doctors use this code when diagnosing patients with suspected rickettsial infections, typically in urgent care or office settings after evaluating symptoms and exposure history. This code may appear on patient EOB statements when lab work or imaging is performed to confirm the diagnosis, though it's usually replaced with a more specific rickettsial disease code once identified.",
