    "rawCode": "A800",
    "shortDesc": "Acute paralytic poliomyelitis, vaccine-associated",
    "longDesc": "Acute paralytic poliomyelitis, vaccine-associated",
    "plainEnglish": "This is a rare type of polio infection that develops as a side effect from receiving the oral polio vaccine (OPV), rather than from naturally acquiring the wild poliovirus. The vaccine contains a weakened live virus designed to build immunity, but in very uncommon cases—especially in people with weak immune systems—the vaccine virus can cause polio symptoms including muscle weakness and paralysis, most often in the legs. This condition is extremely rare in countries using inactivated polio vaccine (IPV injection) and is now primarily a concern only in regions still using the older oral vaccine.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by infectious disease specialists, neurologists, and pediatricians when diagnosing polio-related paralysis in vaccine recipients. It appears in hospital admissions, emergency department visits, and infectious disease consultations, and would be reported on patient EOB statements when hospitalization or specialist care is required. Public health agencies also track this code to monitor vaccine safety and adverse events.",
