    "shortDesc": "Acute paralytic poliomyelitis, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Acute paralytic poliomyelitis, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Acute paralytic poliomyelitis is a rare but serious viral infection caused by the poliovirus that damages the nerve cells controlling muscles, leading to sudden weakness or paralysis. This condition typically starts with fever, headache, and muscle pain, but in severe cases progresses to permanent paralysis of the legs, arms, or even the breathing muscles. The 'unspecified' designation means the doctor has confirmed the patient has this paralytic form of polio but hasn't documented which specific type of poliovirus (wild-type or vaccine-derived) caused it.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, neurologists, and emergency medicine physicians use this code when diagnosing a patient with acute polio-related paralysis, typically in hospitalization or emergency department settings. This code is rare in modern practice due to polio vaccination programs but would appear on patient EOB statements if a case were identified, triggering public health notification requirements.",
