    "shortDesc": "Acute nonparalytic poliomyelitis",
    "longDesc": "Acute nonparalytic poliomyelitis",
    "plainEnglish": "Acute nonparalytic poliomyelitis is a viral infection caused by the poliovirus that affects the nervous system but does NOT cause permanent paralysis. Patients experience sudden fever, severe muscle pain and stiffness (especially in the back and neck), fatigue, and sometimes meningitis-like symptoms, but their muscles maintain normal function. This is a milder form of polio infection compared to the paralytic type, though it can still be quite uncomfortable and debilitating temporarily.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and primary care doctors use this code when diagnosing polio cases in clinical settings—typically in emergency departments or during hospitalization for acute illness evaluation. This code rarely appears on patient EOB statements in most developed countries due to widespread polio vaccination, but it may be used in unvaccinated populations or in countries where polio remains endemic.",
