    "shortDesc": "Acute poliomyelitis, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Acute poliomyelitis, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Poliomyelitis is a viral infection caused by the poliovirus that attacks the nerve cells in the spinal cord, leading to muscle weakness or paralysis. When the code says 'unspecified,' it means the doctor has confirmed the patient has acute polio but hasn't documented which specific form or which nerves are affected. The infection typically causes fever, muscle pain, and can progress to temporary or permanent paralysis of the legs, arms, or breathing muscles.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists and emergency medicine doctors use this code when diagnosing a patient with confirmed poliomyelitis in hospital or urgent care settings. Because polio is rare in developed countries due to vaccination, this code appears infrequently on patient EOBs but would be used in cases of disease outbreak investigations or in unvaccinated populations; it's more commonly seen in public health reporting and epidemiological tracking.",
    "billable": true,
