    "longDesc": "Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) is a rare, rapidly progressive brain disorder caused by misfolded proteins called prions that damage and destroy brain tissue. The condition leads to severe mental decline, loss of muscle control, memory problems, and personality changes, and it is always fatal, usually within a year of symptom onset. There is no cure, and the disease progresses very quickly, causing severe disability and dementia in its final stages.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, infectious disease specialists, and hospital-based physicians typically diagnose and manage CJD, often through specialized referral centers or teaching hospitals. This code is used in inpatient settings (hospitals, skilled nursing facilities) and appears on patient bills and EOB statements when patients are hospitalized or receive advanced diagnostic testing like MRI or cerebrospinal fluid analysis for this condition.",
