    "shortDesc": "Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy",
    "longDesc": "Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy",
    "plainEnglish": "Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy (PML) is a rare and serious brain infection caused by a virus called JC virus that damages the white matter (the nerve fibers) in multiple areas of the brain. This condition typically only develops in people with severely weakened immune systems, such as those with advanced HIV/AIDS or taking strong immunosuppressant medications. Symptoms include progressive weakness, vision problems, difficulty speaking, confusion, and loss of coordination, and the condition worsens over time without treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, infectious disease specialists, and HIV/AIDS physicians diagnose and manage PML. This code appears on EOB statements primarily for patients with advanced immunodeficiency disorders who require hospitalization, imaging studies, lumbar punctures, or specialist consultations. It is considered a serious AIDS-defining illness and typically triggers comprehensive workup and treatment planning.",
