    "longDesc": "Sylvatic rabies",
    "plainEnglish": "Sylvatic rabies is a form of rabies infection that occurs in wild animals such as bats, raccoons, skunks, and foxes, and can be transmitted to humans through bites or scratches. This is different from urban rabies, which spreads through domesticated dogs. Once symptoms appear in humans—including fever, numbness at the bite site, anxiety, confusion, hallucinations, and paralysis—the infection is almost always fatal without immediate post-exposure prophylaxis (vaccination and immunoglobulin treatment).",
