    "shortDesc": "West Nile virus infection with encephalitis",
    "longDesc": "West Nile virus infection with encephalitis",
    "plainEnglish": "West Nile virus is a mosquito-borne infection that in some cases spreads to the brain and causes encephalitis, which is inflammation of the brain tissue. This can lead to serious symptoms like high fever, severe headache, confusion, muscle weakness, and in severe cases, paralysis or loss of consciousness. Most people infected with West Nile virus don't develop encephalitis, but those who do require hospitalization and intensive care.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, neurologists, and emergency medicine physicians use this code when diagnosing West Nile virus patients with confirmed brain inflammation. This code commonly appears in hospital settings and on EOB statements for patients requiring hospitalization, imaging studies, and intensive care during the summer and fall mosquito season when cases are more prevalent.",
