    "shortDesc": "Rift Valley fever",
    "longDesc": "Rift Valley fever",
    "plainEnglish": "Rift Valley fever is a serious viral infection spread to humans through bites from infected mosquitoes and other insects, or by contact with infected animal blood and tissues. The disease causes sudden fever, severe headache, muscle and joint pain, weakness, and can progress to more dangerous complications like bleeding, liver damage, or eye problems in severe cases. It's primarily found in Africa and the Arabian Peninsula, where outbreaks occur when heavy rains increase mosquito populations.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, emergency medicine physicians, and tropical medicine experts use this code, typically in patients presenting with fever and systemic symptoms in endemic regions or travelers returning from affected areas. It commonly appears on EOB statements for hospitalized patients or those requiring specialized treatment, and is reportable to public health authorities as a notifiable disease in most countries.",
