    "rawCode": "A925",
    "shortDesc": "Zika virus disease",
    "longDesc": "Zika virus disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Zika virus disease is an infection spread by Aedes mosquitoes (the same mosquitoes that carry dengue and chikungunya) that causes fever, rash, joint pain, and headache lasting a few days to a week. While most people recover without serious complications, the virus is particularly concerning because it can cause severe birth defects, including microcephaly (abnormally small head and brain), if a pregnant woman gets infected. The infection is often mild and may go unnoticed, but some people experience more noticeable symptoms like muscle pain and fatigue.",
    "whoUses": "Infectious disease specialists, family medicine doctors, and obstetricians use this code when diagnosing Zika virus infection, particularly during pregnancy screening and in travelers returning from endemic areas. It appears on EOB statements for patients with confirmed Zika diagnosis who receive treatment or monitoring, though it became less common after the initial outbreak years and now primarily affects pregnant women or those in outbreak regions.",
